reviews.review_text: CHARLIE, JUST WANTED TO SAY... A BIG "THANK YOU !" for all you do for the GD archive !  Thanks to you and peeps like you, WE get to keep on Truckin' ! n

Balanced and breezy in Mountain View ‘92 This band leaves me scratching my head sometimes. This show has moments of sheer brilliance. And yet, there’s a few mishaps where they fumble the rhythm or fluff easy lyrics. It’s like watching a running back weaving and spinning through the defensive line and sprinting 70 yards, only to trip over his own laces just before reaching the end zone. Luckily, the good moments are great, and far outweigh the innocent blunders.

On paper, this looks like a traditional 80’s setlist. There’s no So Many Roads, Wave to the Wind, or Vince tunes, interestingly enough. Instead, they broke in Night 1 of the Shoreline run with trusty classics. Bill Kreutzmann’s subtle, tasteful drumming carries it all along, and Jerry uses Rosebud to flower the performance with beautifully pure, potent, and melodic solos. Contrasting counterweights collide, in the form of Mickey’s diagonal chopping and Weir’s fizzing against-the-grain chords and slide guitar. True to 90’s protocol, Lesh is way up in the mix and full of anticipatory trickery, making the whole punch bowl a little stronger. Welnick’s textures and effects are floaty and atmospheric. When he goes overboard he risks stepping on toes, but when he settles in the sweet spot, he lends lovely landscapes to tunes like Candyman, Box of Rain, and an intensely psychedelic The Wheel. You can tell a lot about a show from its Playing in the Band jam, and this is no exception; they were musically alert and balanced on 5/23/92. Also of note: the instrumental jam out of Stella Blue contains some of the purest notes I’ve heard from Captain Trips. Simple, yet beautiful.

I for one think Jerry’s vocals in the 90’s were powerful. Yes, his voice was more raw and weathered than it'd been in decades past, but I think you have to have lived a few decades, seen some sobering things, and had a few brushes with death to give this much chilling surrender to words such as:

Come take these guns off of me
I won’t shoot them anymore
The sun is setting over me
And I feel like I must be knockin’ on Heaven’s door, Heaven’s door.

In all, this show amounts to an impressive display of GD musicianship. There’s no dynamite moments that jump out and blast your socks off. Rather, there are clever contributions, subtle passages, and glimpses of harmonious group-thinking that lure your attention and catch your ear. Another nice '90s Shoreliner from the best band in the land!
